    <section class="faq">
      <h2>Extreme FAQ: 280E Edition</h2>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I deduct my CEO's six-figure salary?</summary>
        <p>No. Under 280E, you cannot deduct salaries or compensation for any employee, including executives, that exceeds what's considered "reasonable." The IRS scrutinizes cannabis company payroll aggressively, and many deductions get rejected. Work with a cannabis-specific accountant to structure compensation properly.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What happens if I mix personal and business expenses?</summary>
        <p>This is one of the fastest ways to trigger an audit. The IRS uses 280E to deny all deductions for businesses with sloppy record-keeping. Keep separate bank accounts, credit cards, and meticulous records. If you can't prove it's a business expense, you can't deduct it.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I deduct marketing and advertising costs?</summary>
        <p>Not traditionally. While marketing is a normal business expense for most industries, 280E specifically prohibits cannabis businesses from deducting advertising expenses. However, you may be able to deduct some marketing costs as part of Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) if they're directly tied to product production.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What about my retail space rent?</summary>
        <p>Retail rent is typically non-deductible under 280E. The same applies to utilities, maintenance, and other occupancy costs for your commercial space. This is why many cannabis businesses structure as "dual-entity" models—one company handles cultivation/production (where some costs ARE deductible), and a separate retail entity handles sales.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Are vehicle expenses deductible?</summary>
        <p>Only if you can prove the vehicle is used exclusively for business. A delivery vehicle? Deductible. A car you use for personal errands too? Not deductible. The IRS requires detailed mileage logs and proof of exclusive business use for any vehicle deduction.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I write off my business insurance?</summary>
        <p>Generally no. Like other typical business expenses, insurance premiums are disallowed under 280E. However, your insurance costs factor into your COGS calculation, which CAN be deducted. Make sure your accountant is capturing all insurance costs in your cost of goods sold.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What qualifies as Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)?</summary>
        <p>COGS is your lifeline under 280E. It includes: direct costs of producing or acquiring inventory (cultivation costs, product purchase costs, testing fees, packaging, labeling, portion of labor, and overhead directly tied to production). Maximizing COGS reduces your taxable income more than any deduction strategy.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Do I really need a cannabis-specific accountant?</summary>
        <p>Absolutely. The complexity of 280E compliance requires specialized expertise. A general CPA may not understand the nuances of COGS allocation, multi-entity structures, or Maine-specific tax obligations. The cost of a specialist is far less than the cost of an audit or mistakes that result in penalties.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can I use an S-Corporation to avoid 280E?</summary>
        <p>No. The S-Corp election doesn't help with 280E—the limitation applies at the entity level regardless of pass-through taxation. However, S-Corps may benefit from the Section 199A deduction (20% QBI), which can provide meaningful savings. The analysis depends on your specific situation.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What happens if I get audited and lose?</summary>
        <p>If the IRS challenges your COGS allocations or other deductions, you face back taxes, interest, and potentially penalties of 20-75%. In severe cases, they may pursue fraud charges. This is why proper documentation and cannabis-experienced representation are essential.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

